soviet dictator josef stalin was a harsh man of 
few words but he occasionally gave in to softer human emotions 
former soviet foreign minister andrei gromyko said in an excerpt 
from his memoirs published sunday 
the first of a series of excerpts from gromykos book 
memories appeared in the observer newspaper 
an example gromyko gives of stalins more human side was in his 
relations with us president franklin d roosevelt when they were 
allies during world war ii gromyko was ambassador to the united 
states 
during the february 1945 yalta meeting between stalin roosevelt 
and british prime minister winston churchill roosevelt became ill 
one day and the talks were suspended the president who was 
crippled by polio at the age of 39 lived only two months after the 
yalta conference 
gromyko said he accompanied stalin on a 20minute visit to 
roosevelt who was in bed in his room overlooking the crimean sea 
and they exchanged remarks about health and the weather and beauty 
of the soviet crimea 
the president was delighted to see us he was clearly 
tired and drained though he tried not to show it gromyko wrote 
we were descending the narrow staircase when stalin suddenly 
stopped took his pipe out of his pocket filled it unhurriedly 
and as if to himself said quietly why did nature have to 
punish him so is he worse than other people 
despite his basic harshness of character stalin did just 
occasionally give way to positive human emotions gromyko said 
describing stalins manner he said i was always aware 
watching stalin speaking of how expressive his face was 
especially his eyes when rebuking or arguing with someone stalin 
had a way of staring him mercilessly in the eyes and not taking his 
gaze off him the object of this relentless stare one has to 
admit felt profoundly uncomfortable 
he spoke quietly evenly almost as if muffled and raised his 
voice rarely even so whenever he spoke there was total silence 
however many people were there gromyko said 
